      \field{abstract}{The U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) is estimated to regulate markets accounting for about 20\% of consumer spending in the U.S. Despite the FDA's strict adherence to evidence-based evaluation of the safety and efficacy of the products it regulates, there exists no generally agreed upon evidence-based methodology to evaluate the agency's own safety and efficacy record. This paper proposes a methodology to evaluate FDA policies in general, and the central speed-safety tradeoff it faces, in particular. We apply this methodology to estimate the welfare effects of a major piece of legislation affecting this tradeoff, the Prescription Drug User Fee Acts (PDUFA). These acts mandated FDA performance goals in reviewing and acting on drug applications within specified time periods, in return for levying fees on drug manufacturers' submissions. Our methodology uses data on the U.S. sales of drugs as well as the FDA review and withdrawal times for those drugs to estimate measures of the private and social surplus associated with the agency in general, and changes in the speed-safety tradeoff induced by PDUFA, in particular. We find that PDUFA raised the private surplus of producers, and thus innovative returns, by about \$7 to \$11 billion. Depending on assumptions about the market power of producers during patent protection, we find that PDUFA raised consumer welfare between \$7 and \$20 billion; thus the combined social surplus was raised by \$14 to \$31 billion. Converting these economic gains into equivalent health benefits, we find that the more rapid access of drugs on the market enabled by PDUFA saved the equivalent of 140,000 to 310,000 life years. Additionally, we estimate an upper bound on the adverse effects of PDUFA based on drugs submitted during PDUFA I/II and subsequently withdrawn for safety reasons, and find that an extreme upper bound of about 56,000 life years were lost. This estimate is an extreme upper bound as it assumes all withdrawals since the inception of PDUFA were due to PDUFA and that there were no patients who benefitted from the withdrawn drugs. We discuss how our general methodology could be used to perform a quantitative and evidence-based evaluation of the desirability of other FDA policies in the future, particularly those affecting the speed-safety tradeoff of the agency.}
      \field{issn}{0047-2727}
      \field{journaltitle}{Journal of Public Economics}
      \field{month}{6}
      \field{note}{Paper: \par Philipson, Tomas, Ernst Berndt, Adrian Gottschalk, and Eric Sun (2008) \par "Cost-benefit analysis of the FDA: The case of the Prescription Drug User Fee Acts" \par Journal of Public Economics 92: 1306--1325. \par 1. Research Question: \par What are the welfare effects of the Prescription Drug User Fee Acts (PDUFA), which were designed to speed up FDA drug approval times? \par More broadly, the paper asks how to evaluate the FDA's central policy trade-off between: \par - faster access to drugs (speed of approval) \par - potential safety risks (harm from unsafe drugs) \par The authors develop a framework to estimate the welfare effects of regulatory speed. \par 2. Data: \par The analysis uses several types of data: \par - U.S. drug sales data \par - FDA drug approval review times \par - FDA drug withdrawal data (drugs later removed for safety reasons) \par - Information on timing of market entry \par - Data on drug patent protection and market structure \par These data allow the authors to estimate the economic value of faster access to new drugs and the costs associated with potential safety risks. \par 3. Identification: \par The empirical strategy exploits the introduction of PDUFA as a policy change that significantly reduced FDA drug review times. \par PDUFA (starting in 1992) allowed the FDA to collect user fees from pharmaceutical companies in exchange for meeting review-time targets. \par The authors compare outcomes before and after the policy change to estimate how faster approval times affected: \par - drug availability \par - producer profits \par - consumer welfare \par - safety risks (via withdrawal rates) \par The key identification assumption is that PDUFA created a measurable exogenous increase in regulatory speed. \par 4. Main Results: \par The authors find that PDUFA substantially reduced drug approval times and generated large welfare gains. \par Key results include: \par - PDUFA increased producer surplus (innovative returns) by roughly \$7--\$11 billion. \par - Consumer welfare gains are estimated between \$7--\$20 billion due to faster access to new drugs. \par - Faster approval allows patients to benefit earlier from new therapies. \par - The welfare benefits from earlier access outweigh the expected costs associated with drug withdrawals. \par Overall conclusion: \par The benefits of faster access to drugs appear to exceed the costs associated with increased safety risk. \par 5. Limitations: \par Several important limitations exist. \par First, the analysis focuses on the speed-safety trade-off in terms of drug withdrawals, which is only one dimension of safety risk. \par Second, the paper does not examine behavioral outcomes such as: \par - prescribing patterns \par - misuse \par - drug diversion \par - illicit market spillovers \par Third, welfare calculations rely on assumptions about: \par - market power during patent protection \par - consumer surplus from earlier drug access \par - the relationship between approval speed and safety risk. \par Finally, the study evaluates aggregate welfare effects rather than distributional impacts across patient groups or drug classes. \par 6. How this connects to MY project: \par This paper provides the foundational economic framework for thinking about the consequences of faster FDA drug approval. \par Philipson et al. frame the core policy problem as a "speed vs safety" trade-off. Their analysis focuses on whether faster approval leads to harmful drugs reaching the market. \par My project extends this framework by considering an additional potential externality that the paper does not examine: drug diversion and misuse. \par Specifically: \par Regulatory acceleration {$\rightarrow$} earlier and potentially greater pharmaceutical supply {$\rightarrow$} increased opportunities for diversion into illicit markets. \par While Philipson et al. evaluate safety risks primarily through drug withdrawals, my project investigates whether faster regulatory approval could generate downstream effects in illicit drug markets. \par Thus, this paper establishes the upstream mechanism (regulatory speed and drug supply) that motivates the empirical question in my thesis.}
